{"id":"1610.04590","submitter":"Vasilis Chousionis","authors":"Vasileios Chousionis and Sean Li","title":"Nonnegative kernels and $1$-rectifiability in the Heisenberg group","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Analysis & PDE 10 (2017) 1407-1428","doi":"10.2140/apde.2017.10.1407","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA math.FA math.MG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $E$ be an $1$-Ahlfors regular subset of the Heisenberg group\n$\\mathbb{H}$. We prove that there exists a $-1$-homogeneous kernel $K_1$ such\nthat if $E$ is contained in a $1$-regular curve the corresponding singular\nintegral is bounded in $L^2(E)$. Conversely, we prove that there exists another\n$-1$-homogeneous kernel $K_2$, such that the $L^2(E)$-boundedness of its\ncorresponding singular integral implies that $E$ is contained in an $1$-regular\ncurve. These are the first non-Euclidean examples of kernels with such\nproperties. Both $K_1$ and $K_2$ are weighted versions of the Riesz kernel\ncorresponding to the vertical component of $\\mathbb{H}$. Unlike the Euclidean\ncase, where all known kernels related to rectifiability are antisymmetric, the\nkernels $K_1$ and $K_2$ are even and nonnegative.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Oct 2016 19:23:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-17"}
